s","includeInTable":true},"columnOrder":0,"originalMetadata":null,"datasetName":"Average effective age of retirement, by gender (OECD, 2018)","s_id":17958,"s_name":"Average effective age of retirement, by gender (OECD, 2018)","source":{"id":17958,"name":"Average effective age of retirement, by gender (OECD, 2018)","dataPublishedBy":"OECD Database on Average Effective Retirement Age","dataPublisherSource":"National labour force surveys, EU Labour Force Survey, and national censuses","link":"http://www.oecd.org/els/emp/average-effective-age-of-retirement.htm","retrievedData":"","additionalInfo":"The average effective age of retirement is calculated as a weighted average of (net) labour market withdrawals at different ages over a 5-year period for workers initially aged 40 and over.\n\nThe estimate for each year corresponds to the 5 year interval leading up to that year. For example, the observation for 1970 corresponds to (1965-70), 1971 to (1966-71) etc. \n\nLabour force withdrawals are estimated based on changes in labour force participation rates rather than labour force levels to abstract from compositional effects. Estimates include both interpolations of census data as well as labour force surveys. For a breakdown by observation, see the <a href=\"http://www.oecd.org/els/emp/Summary_1970%20values.xlsx\">following spreadsheet<a>. The Austria series uses interpolations of census data from 1970-1998 and annual labour force survey estimates from 1999 onward, while the 'Austria (alternative)' series refers to estimates taken from the annual labour force survey from 1970-2003, for both the women and men's series.\n\nNote: The estimates for women in Turkey are based on 3-yearly moving averages of participation rates for each 5-year age group."}}},"entityKey":{"1":{"name":"United Kingdom","code":"GBR"},"2":{"name":"Ireland","code":"IRL"},"3":{"name":"France","code":"FRA"},"4":{"name":"Belgium","code":"BEL"},"5":{"name":"Netherlands","code":"NLD"},"6":{"name":"Germany","